Title: What Lurks Behind The Mask: Shining Light On The Innermost Environments Of Directly Imaged Host Stars

PI: Czekala, Ian - Stanford University

Type: N/A

Summary: We propose two-minute TESS observations of a sample of 481 directly imaged young and intermediate age stars in order to characterize the distribution of material on their innermost orbits. We will search for the closest ``dipper'' events---belived to be the result of magnetospheric accretion or disk warping due to a companion---and, with a set of well characterized stellar properties, measure the occurence rate of the dipper phenomenon with stellar properties and circumstellar environment. We will also search the dozen disks with known edge-on inclinations for disk-transit events. We will derive rotation periods for all sources with rotation-modulated lightcurves to improve their age estimates, which are vital to understanding the completeness of direct imaging exoplanet surveys.
